{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492514"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:34:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:34:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1088"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1088"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.54,0.37,0,0.06,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1088"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76754"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1088","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1088"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1088"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62247"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1789"},{"type":"tags","id":"3564"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7605"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8033"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42216"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76754"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise fit and healthy 21-year-old woman presents to a new General Practice for advice on changes in her hands (Image). She says her hands have looked like this for many years, but the changes have become more noticeable recently. Her hands are not itchy or tender. She recalls that her late aunt reported similar symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Congenital Keratoderma","Carotenaemia","Scabies","Discoid lupus erythematosus","Vitiligo"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is an image of palmoplantar \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratoderma\u003C/strong\u003E. Keratoderma can be inherited or acquired, and presents with thickening of the skin of the palms of the hands and/or soles of the feet. The thickening may be diffuse or focal, localised to pressure areas on the surface of the palms or the soles. Management involves softening thickened skin, such as with emollients, keratolytic agents, topical retinoids, and/or oral retinoids.  \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarotenaemia\u003C/strong\u003E, which occurs due to to excess consumption of carotene-rich food, is characterised by yellow pigmentation of the skin and increased beta-carotene levels in the blood. \u003Cstrong\u003EDiscoid lupus erythematosus \u003C/strong\u003Eis the most common type of cutaneous lupus, an autoimmune skin condition which commonly is located on scalp, face, upper torso and can involve photosensitive sites of limbs, not the palms.  \u003Cstrong\u003EVitiligo\u003C/strong\u003E is a depigmenting disorder of the skin, resulting from autoimmune destruction of melanocytes. \u003Cstrong\u003EScabies\u003C/strong\u003E is a parasitic infection by Sarcoptes scabies, leading to an itchy rash.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Keratoderma is a condition that results in marked thickening of the epidermis of the skin.","Inherited forms of keratoderma often have a family history and present early in life."],"references":["Stanway A. Palmoplantar keratoderma [Internet]. DermNet. 2016 [cited 2022 Oct 13]. Available from: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/palmoplantar-keratoderma","Dev T, Mahajan VK, Sethuraman G. Hereditary Palmoplantar Keratoderma: A Practical Approach to the Diagnosis. Indian Dermatol Online J. 2019 Jul-Aug;10(4):365-379. doi: 10.4103/idoj.IDOJ_367_18. PMID: 31334055; PMCID: PMC6615398.","Thomas BR, O\u0027Toole EA. Diagnosis and Management of Inherited Palmoplantar Keratodermas. Acta Derm Venereol. 2020 Mar 25;100(7):adv00094. doi: 10.2340/00015555-3430. PMID: 32147745; PMCID: PMC9128927."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62247"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1088"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"19015"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"19015","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/19015"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ad8367a1-3316-4eaa-8da3-d58065cadcc2.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ad8367a1-3316-4eaa-8da3-d58065cadcc2.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62247","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62247"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-04T20:15:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T20:15:09+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1088"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76754"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"